4.1.4 Plot 4

Special thanks to Shuyi for helping me with the logic of this one.

d <- d |> 
  mutate(z4_log_odds = x + y,
         z4_pp = exp(z4_log_odds)/(1 + exp(z4_log_odds)),
         z4 = as.logical(rbinom(N, 1, z4_pp)))

plot4 <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x, y, fill= z4)) +
          geom_point(shape = "circle filled", 
                      size = 1.75,
                     color = "black") + 
          scale_fill_manual(values = c(alpha("red", 0.75), 
                                       alpha("blue", 0.5))) +
         coord_fixed() + xlim(-3.5, 3.5) + ylim(-3.5, 3.5) +
          geom_smooth(data = d |> 
                        filter(z4 == TRUE), 
                               method = "lm", 
                               color = "blue", 
                               fill=alpha("blue", 0.25)) +
          geom_smooth(data = d |> 
                        filter(z4 == FALSE),
                      method = "lm",
                      color = "red",
                      fill = alpha("red", 0.25))

Exercise 4.2

Term Definition
Conditional average treatment effect This is the average of the effect of the treatment conditional on something- usually, the treatment effect for a specified subset of the population. (Men, women, parents, etc. Depends on RQ; Huntington-Klein says you should condition the ATE for a drug on cervical cancer to those with cervices. Makes sense- why would I included those w/o cervices?)
Average treatment effect on the treated (ATT) Conditions the average effect of treatment on only those who received treatment; probably most common form of a conditional ATE
Average treatment effect on the untreated (ATU) Conditions the average effect of treatment on only those who did not receive treatment; less common, but helpful if you want to know how treatment varies, or what causes big/small treatment effects. often, ATT/ATU arenât the same due to a baseline bias. the groups for T==1 and T==0 might be categorically different in some way.

Exercise 4.3

Provide an example of a treatment effect that you would expect to be highly heterogeneous, and explain why you think it is likely to be heterogeneous.

I suspect the treatment of an experimental drug on mental health (maybe on a scale from 0 to 10, 0 being absolute misery and 10 being absolute happiness) would be highly heterogeneous- namely because âmental healthâ is extremely variable to begin with. It would be difficult to isolate the effect of the drug on an individualâs mental health because so many things contribute to it: physical health, employment status & satisfaction, life satisfaction, social networks, strength of relationships, stress, and so on.

Exercise 4.4

Case Age Gender Effect
A 15 Man 7
B 40 Woman 3
C 30 Woman 7
D 20 Non-binary 8
E 15 Man 7
F 25 Woman 4

a. What is the overall average treatment effect for the population?

(7 + 3 + 7 + 8 + 7 + 4)/6
[1] 6

\(\text{ATE} = 6\) for the population.

b. What is the average treatment effect for Women?

(3 + 7 + 4)/3
[1] 4.666667

\(\text{ATE}_{women} = 4.67\)

c. If nearly all Non-binary people get treated, and about half of all Women get treated, and we control for the differences between Women and Non-binary people, what kind of treatment effect average will we get, and what can we say about the numerical estimate weâll get?

This will get us a variance-weighted treatment effect. Since about half the women get treated, and nearly all non-binary people get treated, there is variance in who gets treated. Since half women get treated and half do not, the variance in treatment among women is .25 (0.5 * 0.5). Since nearly all non-binary people get treated, the variance in treatment among non-binary folks is very small (assuming probability that a non-binary person gets treated is 0.95, the variance in treatment is 0.95 * 0.05 = 0.0475).

This estimate will weight the treatment effect of those with greater variation in treatment more heavily. This means that in the above example, the estimate will be closer to the treatment effect for women (since there is so littleâ in fact, almost no- variation in the treatment for non-binary folks).

d. If we assume that, in the absence of treatment, everyone would have had the same outcome, and also only teenagers (19 or younger) ever receive treatment, and we compare treated people to control people, what kind of treatment effect average will we get, and what can we say about the numerical estimate weâll get?

This will get us a conditional average treatment effect- the average will be calculated on the condition that an individual is a teenager. This estimate will be weighted towards those who meet the condition specified.

Exercise 4.5

Give an example where the average treatment effect on the treated would be more useful to consider than the overall average treatment effect, and explain why.

The ATT is more beneficial than the overall ATE in instances where the treatment is only intended to work for a particular subset of the population. Letâs say I wanted to find the effect of âflippedâ classrooms (where lecture is delivered at home, and class time is devoted to homework) on student outcomes. I wouldnât really be interested in student outcomes in general. Iâd want to focus in on those who receive treatment.

Or, to borrow from the book, if Iâm testing a drug on its effects on the prevalence of prostate cancer, I wouldnât want to look at the effect among the entire population, Iâd just want to focus on the treatment group (ie people with prostates).

Exercise 4.8

Suppose you are conducting an experiment to see whether pricing cookies at $1.99 versus $2 affects the decision to purchase the cookies. The population of interest is all adults in the United States. You recruit people from your university to participate and randomize them to either see cookies priced as $1.99 or $2, then write down whether they purchased cookies. What kind of average treatment effect can you identify from this experiment?

This would be conditional average treatment effect- the condition is that all individuals sampled are in college (whether or not they received treatment).

Exercise 4.9

For each of the following identification strategies, what kind of treatment effect(s) is most likely to be identified?

  1. A randomized experiment using a representative sample

    ATE (Average Treatment Effect)

  2. True randomization within only a certain demographic group

    CATE (Conditional Average Treatment Effect)

  3. Closing back door paths connected to variation in treatment

    Variance-Weighted Average Treatment Effect

  4. Isolating the part of the variation in treatment variable that is driven by an exogenous variable

    Local Average Treatment Effect

  5. The control group is comparable to the treatment group, but treatment effects may be different across these groups

    Heterogeneous Treatment Effect
